\begin_layout Abstract
There are different classes of nonlocal correlations and we derive criteria
 for all of these nonlocal correlations.
 We also focus on understanding nonlocal correlations in multipartite systems
 and provide unambiguous definitions for genuine multipartite nonlocal correlati
ons for each of the classes.
 This is important in our attempt to study the boundary of quantum and classical
 mechanics.
 We apply our criteria to multipartite mesoscopic systems such as the continuous
-variable quantum optical system and quantum optomechanical system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum mechanics allows for nonlocal correlations that cannot be explained
 using pre-determined agreement (that is given by local variables).
 In order to confirm the existence of these nonlocal correlations, criteria
 can be derived such that violation of them implies these nonlocal correlations.
 The most famous criterion in terms of inequality is the Bell's inequality
 that shows disagreement between quantum mechanics and local realism.
 In reality (experiments, that is), any correlations manifest themselves
 in the statistics of the measurement outcomes of some quantities.
 In the next section, we show that different explanations of the statistics
 give us different classes of nonlocal correlations.
 The different definitions of nonlocal correlations can be generalized to
 multipartite systems.
 Based on the definitions of these nonlocal correlations, we derive criteria
 that allow us to check for all these correlations in terms of the statistics
 of quantities from the measurement outcomes in experiments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Quick review on different classes of nonlocal correlations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notion of quantum entanglement has been suggested by Schrodinger
