\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\rho=\sum_{i}\eta_{i}\rho_{Q,1}^{(i)}\rho_{Q,2}^{(i)}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Q,j}^{(i)}$
\end_inset

 is the describes the state of party j and the subscript Q denotes the state
 as a quantum state.
 Hence, two parties are not entangled if the total state can be expressed
 as the product state of the states of each party.
 Since we want to study these nonlocal correlations in terms of statistics,
 we provide here an equivalent definition of quantum entanglement in terms
 of probabilities.
 We say that two parties share quantum entanglement if and only if the statistic
s of some measurement outcomes cannot be expressed as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign}
P(a,b|A,B) & =\sum_{i}\lambda_{i}P_{Q}(a|A,\lambda)P_{Q}(b|B,\lambda)
\end{flalign}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a,b|A,B)$
\end_inset

 is the joint probability of getting outcomes 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 given the measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{Q}(a|A,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is measured that is allowed by quantum mechanics and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a set of local variables that is our explanation for the observed correlatio
ns in the statistics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is by no means the only way to explain the correlations that we see
 in the statistics of measurement outcomes.
 Indeed, the observed statistics could have the following explanation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign}
P(a,b|A,B) & =\sum_{i}\lambda_{i}P(a|A,\lambda)P(b|B,\lambda)
\end{flalign}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(a|A,\lambda)$
\end_inset

 is probability of getting 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is measured that satisfies the properties of probability.
 This constitutes another class of nonlocal correlation and the system is
 said to have Bell nonlocal correlations if the observed statistics cannot
 be expressed as the above form.
 In fact, the above definition is used by Bell to derive his important Bell's
 inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is also an intermediate class of nonlocal correlations that is named
 the EPR steering where the observed statistics cannot be expressed as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign}
P(a,b|A,B) & =\sum_{i}\lambda_{i}P_{Q}(a|A,\lambda)P(b|B,\lambda)
\end{flalign}

\end_inset

.
 EPR steering is important in the field of quantum information where the
 notion of trust is considered.
