\begin_layout Subsubsection
Tripartite quantum entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the definition of nonlocal correlations in place, we want to explore
 the concept of multipartite nonlocal correlations.
 We first consider the idea of multipartite quantum entanglement.
 Again, for simplicity, we consider the meaning of tripartite quantum entangleme
nt.
 A straightforward extension of our definition of quantum entanglement to
 tripartite system is that a tripartite state is quantum entangled if and
 only if it cannot be described as product state of each parties, i.e.
 it cannot be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\rho=\sum_{i}\eta_{i}\rho_{Q,1}^{(i)}\rho_{Q,2}^{(i)}\rho_{Q,3}^{(i)}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

 A trivial example shows that this definition is not adequate.
 Consider the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\rho_{Q,1}\rho_{Q,23}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{Q,23}$
\end_inset

 denotes a bipartitie entangled state for subsystem 2 and 3.
 This state clearly cannot be written as equation (5) and hence should be
 considered a tripartite quantum entangled state according to the definition.
 However, it is really a product state of party 1 and bipartite entangled
 state of parties 2 and 3.
 What we really want is quantum entanglement that is being shared among
 all three parties, i.e.
 entanglement that cannot be described with fewer parties.
 
\end_layout

