\begin_layout Subsubsection
Genuine tripartite entanglement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A state is said to be genuinely tripartite entangled if and only if it cannot
 be described as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\rho=P_{1}\sum_{i}\eta_{i}\rho_{1}\rho_{23}+P_{2}\sum_{i'}\eta_{i'}\rho_{2}\rho_{13}+P_{3}\sum_{i''}\eta_{i''}\rho_{3}\rho_{12}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that to detect genuine tripartite entanglement, we need to negate
 that the state of the system is in any of the bipartitions 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}\rho_{23},\rho_{2}\rho_{13}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{3}\rho_{12}$
\end_inset

 or any mixture of them.
 This definition is more general and harder to show than the full tripartite
 inseparability as the latter excludes only each individual bipartition
 but not mixtures of them.
 For instance, a mixture of bipartite entangled states would show full tripartit
e inseparability.
 Hence, the two different definitions of tripartite quantum entanglement
 mean different things but they have been used interchangeably in the literature.
 Note that genuine tripartite entanglement and full tripartite inseparability
 coincide for pure quantum states but not for mixed states.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This definition of genuine tripartite quantum entanglement can be easily
 generalized to N-partite systems and also for other classes of nonlocal
 correlations.
\end_layout

